05824nam a22009135i 9783110776492DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022932025  a97831107764927 a10.1515/97831107764922doi  a(DE-B1597)613099  a(OCoLC)1308508442  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh00aMedieval Multilingual Manuscripts :bCase Studies from Ireland to Japan /ced. by Máire Ní Mhaonaigh, Michael Clarke. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VI, 240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Manuscript Cultures ,x2365-9696 ;v240 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aManuscripts provide rich documentary evidence for understanding the history of cultural life across the breadth of Europe and Asia down through the Middle Ages. Many illustrate engagement between and across languages, in both similar and contrasting ways from east to west. The demarcation of manuscript studies into single-language academic disciplines has often obscured this reality, privileging one constituent part or contributing language from each manuscript rather than exploring the combination as a nuanced and complex whole. This volume seeks to examine manuscripts as integrally united artefacts, respecting the diversity of their constituent elements. Case studies are presented of twelve manuscripts with evidence for various levels of inter-language exchange and collision, from horizons as diverse as the Atlantic West, Carolingian Europe, the Byzantine world, the Silk Road cultures, and east Asia. The essays function individually as discrete contributions, but together they highlight a range of overlapping themes, illustrating language interaction in global religions, pedagogical exchange, and secular society-building.The analogies as well as the concrete points of connection between them underline the value of a cross-disciplinary approach.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aManuscripts, MedievalvCase studies. 4aAsien. 4aEuropa. 4aHandschriftenkunde. 4aManuskript. 4aMehrsprachigkeit. 4aMittelalter. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aEurope.  aMiddle Ages.  aartefact.  amanuscript studies.  amultilingualism.1 aClarke, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFormigatti, Camillo A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalambos, Imre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHøgel, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMhaonaigh, Máire Ní, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoran, Pádraic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNooij, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNí Mhaonaigh, Máire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Hogan, Cillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRand, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaik, Sam van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchrijver, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVergiani, Vincenzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhitman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part o